pr_body:
Following are the changes included in this PR:
1. Included Usage instruction of Heracles.ts. Now one can install and use Heracles.ts on local machine in either browser or in node.js environment. Before it was difficult to figure out the environment requirements and dependencies required along side Heracles in order to use it. 
2. More clear explanation of classes used in Heracles.ts. Earlier it was without any context which made it difficult to understand. Now one can run and see what each class is doing. This doc serves as the starting point.
3. Removed Outdated classes like ResourceEnrichmentProvider.

Fixes #

### Checklist

### Description
<!-- Describe about what this PR does, previous state and new state of the output -->
This PR does following things:
* Moved all the utility functions to utils folder
* Converted JSX to JS. Because: [No longer Recommended](https://github.com/facebook/create-react-app/issues/87#issuecomment-234627904)
* Made Smaller Components to Print Array, Objects which are reused instead of repeating same code over and over again
* Fixed all previous warnings and errors.
* Made services folder to deal with http requests. This separation of concern helped remove nested promises and made code little bit cleaner.
### Change logs

<!-- #### Added -->
<!-- Edit these points below to describe the new features added with this PR -->
<!-- - Feature 1 -->
<!-- - Feature 2 -->


<!-- #### Changed -->
<!-- Edit these points below to describe the changes made in existing functionality with this PR -->
<!-- - Change 1 -->
<!-- - Change 1 -->
* Used smaller generic components like PrintObjects, PrintString, PrintID and PrintArray instead of repeating similar type of code in HydraConsole component
* Created utils/utils.js to contain utility functions to be used in anywhere in the app
* Used strict equality and inequality checks to prevent unwanted type coercion
*  Created services for each HTTP endpoint, to follow separation of concern and removed nested promises which could lead to unexpected results.
